subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Very similar to 

Antodynerus dictatorius

, from which it is differentiated by: shorter clypeus in both sexes (
Fig. 9
), male clypeus with blunter teeth (
Fig. 11
), interspaces on clypeus micropunctate, cephalic foveae placed in a barely differentiated area (
Fig. 10
), male F11 evenly narrowed from base to apex (
Fig. 12
), mesosomal teguments shinier and with larger micropunctures in interspaces, posterior lobe of tegula shorter (
Fig. 13
), T1 shorter, apical lamella of T2 reduced to a narrow translucent margin, T3 with barely visible translucent margin (
Fig. 14
), punctures on basal half of T2 deeper, ventral lobes of aedeagus more projecting ventrolaterally.

Like female, differing as follows: head in frontal view 1.2 × as wide as long, clypeus in frontal view 1.3 × as wide as long, free apical part much shorter than basal interocular part, apical margin semicircularly emarginate and 0.25 × as wide as clypeal width (
Fig. 11
), clypeus in lateral view more convex in basal two thirds, mandible 3-toothed with apical tooth straight and longer than wide, second tooth prolonged in a long cutting margin that occupies about half of inner margin, third tooth subtriangular, short with a very broad base, upper margin adhering to lateral margin of clypeus, F11 claw-shaped in lateral view, dorsal margin evenly convex to the nearly pointed apex, reaching apical third of F8 (
Fig. 12
), gena in lateral view 1.1 × as broad as eye at bottom of ocular sinus, T7 and S7 broadly rounded at apex, clypeus and spot above interantennal space yellow.
